{{Culture of Burundi}} The indigenous population of [[Burundi]] is divided into three major [[ethnic group]]s: [[Hutu]], [[Tutsi]], and [[Great Lakes Twa|Twa]].{{efn|name=ethnic|In most [[Bantu languages]], the [[prefix#Bantu languages|prefix]] ''ba-'' (or ''wa-'') is added to a human noun to form a plural. As such, ''Bahutu'' would refer collectively to members of the Hutu ethnic group, ''Batutsi'' to Tutsi, and ''Batwa'' to the Twa.}} Its ethnic make-up is similar to that of [[Rwanda]].{{sfn|Uvin|1999|p=253}} Tensions between ethnic groups exist and have become violent on several occasions since independence.
Besides native Burundians, other ethnic groups from elsewhere in [[Africa]], [[Europe]], and [[Asia]] are also represented in Burundi as a result of immigration.
==Indigenous population== ===Ethnic groups=== Native Burundians belong to one of the three major ethnic groups in Burundi: the [[Hutu]], [[Tutsi]], and [[Great Lakes Twa|Twa]] peoples. The [[Origins of Hutu and Tutsi|historical origins of ethnic differentiation between Hutu and Tutsi]] are disputed, however members of both groups consider themselves distinct.<ref name=WP/>{{sfn|Uvin|1999|p=254}}
The Hutu are the largest ethnic group in Burundi, representing approximately 80 percent of Burundians.<ref name=WP>{{cite news|last=Jones|first=Cara E.|title=There are signs of renewed ethnic violence in Burundi|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/monkey-cage/wp/2015/12/15/there-are-signs-of-renewed-ethnic-violence-in-burundi/|publisher=The Washington Post|date=15 December 2015|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> Historically, they lived as [[agriculturalists]]. Under Burundi's Tutsi-dominated postcolonial government between 1965 and 2001, the Hutu population was marginalised and subordinated to the Tutsi elites.<ref name=WP/> The first Hutu to become head of state was [[Melchior Ndadaye]] in 1993, although he was assassinated shortly after taking power.{{sfn|Uvin|1999|p=262}} Since the end of the [[Burundian Civil War]] (1993–2005), Hutus have been dominant in political life.<ref name=WP/>
Tutsi represent approximately 19 percent of the national population.<ref name=WP/> Historically, the Tutsi dominated political institutions in Burundi, including the [[Kingdom of Burundi|nation's monarchy]]. They lived as [[pastoralism|pastoralists]]. Even after the abolition of the monarchy in 1966, the subsequent [[dictator|dictatorial regimes]] of [[Michel Micombero]] (1966–76), [[Jean-Baptiste Bagaza]] (1976–87), and [[Pierre Buyoya]] (1987–93) were dominated by Tutsi elites which often consciously discriminated against the Hutu majority.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ndura|first=Elavie|title=Ethnic Relations and Burundi’s Struggle for Sustainable Peace|url=http://docs.house.gov/meetings/FA/FA16/20150722/103782/HHRG-114-FA16-Wstate-NduraE-20150722.pdf|publisher=United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|year=2015|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref>
The Twa are the smallest indigenous ethnic group in Burundi and are a [[pygmy]] people. There are estimated to be between 30–40,000 Twa living in Burundi (one percent of the national population).<ref name=Minoritytwa>{{cite web|title=Twa|url=http://minorityrights.org/minorities/twa/|work=World Directory of Minorities and Indigenous Peoples|publisher=Minority Rights Group International|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> As an ethnic group, they have links to the pygmy peoples of the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]]. They traditionally lived as [[hunter-gatherer]]s and musicians but, following bans on hunting and land re-distribution, now often work as unskilled labourers.<ref name=OHCHR>{{cite web|title=An indigenous community in Burundi battles for equal treatment|url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/NewsEvents/Pages/BatwaDiscriminated.aspx|publisher=[[Office of the High Commissioner on Human Rights]] (United Nations)|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=Minoritytwa/> The Batwa have been economically and politically marginalised by the other two ethnic groups.<ref name=OHCHR/> They are often disproportionately poor and suffer from legal discrimination.<ref name=Minoritytwa/>
===Ethnic tensions and violence=== Since Burundi became independent from [[Ruanda-Urundi|Belgian colonial rule]] in 1962, it has seen extensive violence between members of the Hutu and Tutsi ethnic groups.<ref name=Economist>{{cite news|title=Burundian time-bomb|newspaper=[[The Economist]]|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21697222-killing-rebels-burundi-has-ominous-echoes-rwanda-1994-burundian-time-bomb|date=23 April 2016|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> Ethnic violence peaked in 1972 when 100,000 people, mainly Hutu, were killed by the Tutsi regime in the [[Burundian Genocide]].<ref name=WP/> Twa have also been targeted, specifically in violence directed against the Tutsi with whom they are sometimes associated.<ref name=Minoritytwa/> Ethnic violence has often been attributed to the agitation of political factions attempting to consolidate their power, as well as to competition for resources.{{sfn|Uvin|1999|p=253}} Burundi's ethnic tensions have been compared to those in [[Rwanda]] which saw similar ethnic tension between Hutu and Tutsi flare up into violence on several occasions, notably during the [[Rwandan Genocide]].<ref name=Economist/>
As a measure to limit the possibilities for discrimination, the 2005 [[Constitution of Burundi|Burundian constitution]] prescribes [[Racial quota|ethnic quotas]] (usually 60 percent Hutu to 40 percent Tutsi) in certain government institutions, including [[Military of Burundi|the military]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Twa people in Burundi: "We want to be fully integrated in institutions"|url=http://www.iwacu-burundi.org/englishnews/twa-people-in-burundi-we-want-to-be-fully-integrated-in-institutions/|publisher=IWACU English News|date=23 August 2013|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> Three seats in each house of the Burundian government are allocated to the Twa.<ref name=Minoritytwa/>
==Immigrant ethnic groups== A significant number of recent immigrants live in Burundi. Most come from neighbouring [[Central Africa]]n countries (especially the Congo, [[Tanzania]], and Rwanda) but other come from [[West Africa]]. There are also [[Europe]]an and [[Asia]]n communities in the country numbering approximately 3,000 and 2,000 people respectively.<ref>{{cite news|last=Grira|first=Safwene|title=Plongé dans une crise sécuritaire, le Burundi recense ses étrangers|url=http://aa.com.tr/fr/afrique/plong%C3%A9-dans-une-crise-s%C3%A9curitaire-le-burundi-recense-ses-%C3%A9trangers-/529657|date=1 March 2016|publisher=Anadolu Agency|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Burundi (People and Society)|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/by.html|publisher=CIA World Fact Book|accessdate=7 January 2017}}</ref>
