{{Infobox language |name=Guatuso |nativename=Maléku Jaíka |states=[[Costa Rica]] |ethnicity = 1,070 [[Maleku people]] (200?)<ref name=e18/> |speakers=750 |date=2000 |ref=e18 |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Chibchan languages|Chibchan]] |fam2=[[Votic languages|Votic]] |iso3=gut |glotto=male1297 |glottorefname=Maléku Jaíka }}
The '''Maléku Jaíka language''', also called '''Guatuso''', '''Watuso-Wétar''', and '''Guetar''', is an indigenous language of north central [[Costa Rica]]. It is a [[Chibchan languages|Chibchan language]] and [[Votic languages|Votic language]] spoken by around 300 to 750 indigenous [[Maléku people]]. This language is considered to be endangered according to '''The Endangered Languages Project'''. [[Corobicí language|Corobicí]] is possibly a dialect.
